83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
C-Engrossed
House Bill 4084
Ordered by the House March 3
Including House Amendments dated February 12 and February 23 and
March 3
Introduced and printed pursuant to House Rule 12.00. Presession filed (at the request of Governor Tina Kotek for
Office of the Governor)
SUMMARY
The following summary is not prepared by the sponsors of the measure and is not a part of the body thereof subject
to consideration by the Legislative Assembly. It is an editor’s brief statement of the essential features of the
measure. The statement includes a measure digest written in compliance with applicable readability standards.
Digest: The Act would set up a Joint Permitting Council to run a fast track permit pro-
gram.
The Act would direct certain state agencies to publish a list of certain permits that can
be issued by the agencies.
The Act would adjust certain requirements of the enterprise zone program and restrict
the use of the program for data centers.
The Act would adjust the tax credit for a taxpayer that creates new jobs. (Flesch Read-
ability Score: 67.5).
[Digest: The Act would set up a Joint Permitting Council to run a fast track permit program.]
[The Act would direct certain state agencies to publish a list of certain permits that can be issued
by the agencies.]
[The Act would adjust certain requirements of the enterprise zone program.]
[The Act would give money to OBDD. (Flesch Readability Score: 71.3).]
Establishes the Joint Permitting Council. Directs the council to administer a fast track permit-
ting program.
Directs certain state agencies to publish a catalog of permits related to economic development
projects issued by the agencies within 120 days after the effective date of the Act.
Updates certain requirements and thresholds for the enterprise zone program. Restricts the
use of the program for data centers.
[Appropriates moneys to the Oregon Business Development Department for deposit in the Indus-
trial Site Loan Fund.]
Modifies provisions establishing a personal income or corporate excise tax credit for a
taxpayer that creates new jobs.
Takes effect on the 91st day following adjournment sine die.
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT
2 Relating to economic development; creating new provisions; amending ORS 285C.090, 285C.135,
3 285C.140, 285C.155, 285C.160, 285C.180, 285C.200, 285C.205 and 285C.210 and section 12, chapter
4 ___, Oregon Laws 2026 (Enrolled Senate Bill 1507); and prescribing an effective date.
5 Be It Enacted by the People of the State of Oregon:
6 SECTION 1. (1) The Joint Permitting Council is established within the office of the Gov-
7 ernor. The council consists of the following members appointed by the Governor:
8 (a) One representative of each of the following agencies:
9 (A) The Department of Transportation.
10 (B) The Department of Land Conservation and Development.
11 (C) The State Department of Energy.
12 (D) The Department of State Lands.
13 (E) The Department of Environmental Quality.
14 (F) The Water Resources Department.
NOTE: Matter in boldfaced type in an amended section is new; matter [italic and bracketed] is existing law to be omitted.
New sections are in boldfaced type.
LC 109

C-Eng. HB 4084
1 (G) The State Department of Agriculture.
2 (H) The Oregon Business Development Department.
3 (I) The State Department of Fish and Wildlife.
4 (J) The Oregon Department of Administrative Services.
5 (K) The State Department of Geology and Mineral Industries.
6 (b) Two members with knowledge and experience in economic development.
7 (2) The term of office of each member of the council is four years. A member serves at
8 the pleasure of the Governor. Before the expiration of the term of a member, the Governor
9 shall appoint a successor whose term begins on January 1 of the following year. A member
10 may be reappointed. If there is a vacancy for any cause, the Governor shall make an ap-
11 pointment to become immediately effective for the unexpired term.
12 (3) A member of the council is not entitled to compensation or reimbursement for ex-
13 penses.
14 (4) The council shall elect one of its members as chairperson and another as vice chair-
15 person, for the terms and with the duties and powers necessary for the performance of the
16 functions of such offices as the council determines.
17 (5) A majority of the members of the council constitutes a quorum for the transaction
18 of business.
19 (6) The council shall meet at times and places specified by the chairperson or a majority
20 of the members of the council.
21 (7) The council may employ staff, including but not limited to a permitting specialist.
22 SECTION 2. (1) The Joint Permitting Council established in section 1 of this 2026 Act
23 shall administer a fast track permitting program that allows eligible projects to obtain ex-
24 pedited regulatory approval from state agencies.
25 (2) The council shall establish eligibility criteria for the fast track permitting program.
26 The criteria must require a project to:
27 (a)(A) Exceed $100 million in capital investment, if the project is located within the urban
28 growth boundary of a metropolitan service district organized under ORS chapter 268;
29 (B) Exceed $50 million in capital investment, if the project is not located within the urban
30 growth boundary of a metropolitan service district organized under ORS chapter 268 or
31 within a nonurban county as described in ORS 653.026; or
32 (C) Exceed $25 million in capital investment, if the project is located within a nonurban
33 county as described in ORS 653.026;
34 (b) Require more than one regulatory approval from one state agency, or more than one
35 regulatory approval from more than one state agency;
36 (c) Advance job creation or growth in gross domestic product through a target industry
37 cluster, as defined by the Oregon Business Development Department by rule;
38 (d) Meet readiness criteria established by the council;
39 (e) Demonstrate land use compatibility;
40 (f) Not require renewals of existing permits; and
41 (g) Meet other requirements established by the council.
42 (3)(a) An applicant for the fast track permitting program shall submit a project applica-
43 tion to the council. The council shall:
44 (A) Review the application to determine if the project meets the eligibility criteria es-
45 tablished under subsection (2) of this section and report the findings to the Governor; and
[2]

C-Eng. HB 4084
1 (B) Forward the application to the Regional Solutions Program created under ORS
2 284.754.
3 (b) The Regional Solutions Program shall review the project, for consistency with re-
4 gional economic development priorities as established under ORS 284.754, Comprehensive
5 Economic Development Strategies or other similar sources, and report to the Governor with
6 a recommendation about whether to advance the project. The report may include additional
7 local or regional dynamics for the Governor to consider.
8 (c) The Governor shall review each application forwarded by the council and the Regional
9 Solutions Program and determine whether to approve the application.
10 (d) The Governor may not approve an application if there are 15 projects currently in
11 progress under the fast track permitting program.
12 (4) If the Governor approves a project application for the fast track permitting program,
13 the council shall:
14 (a) Develop and approve a cooperative project plan for the project that:
15 (A) Includes intermediate and final completion dates for all state regulatory approvals;
16 (B) Provides for a shorter timeline than existing timelines for permitting or other rele-
17 vant timelines for permitting established through policy, law or regulation; and
18 (C) Is consistent with analyses completed by the regulating agencies identifying oppor-
19 tunities to streamline the approval process for the permit, eliminate any unnecessary steps
20 or barriers, reduce the incidence of incomplete applications and eliminate any obsolete or
21 unnecessary approval processes.
22 (b) Identify a lead agency that will provide monthly updates on the project to the council.
23 (c) Include in the plan any other elements deemed necessary by the council.
24 (5) The council shall submit an annual report to the Governor and the Oregon Depart-
25 ment of Administrative Services that describes the status of each project administered in the
26 previous year under the fast track permitting program.
27 SECTION 3. (1) The Governor shall appoint the members of the Joint Permitting Council
28 under section 1 of this 2026 Act no later than July 1, 2026.
29 (2) The Joint Permitting Council shall establish eligibility criteria for the fast track per-
30 mitting program, including readiness criteria, under section 2 of this 2026 Act no later than
31 October 1, 2026.
32 SECTION 4. Section 5 of this 2026 Act is added to and made a part of ORS chapter 183.
33 SECTION 5. (1) This section applies to the following agencies and offices:
34 (a) The Department of Transportation.
35 (b) The Department of Land Conservation and Development.
36 (c) The State Department of Energy.
37 (d) The Department of State Lands.
38 (e) The Department of Environmental Quality.
39 (f) The Water Resources Department.
40 (g) The State Department of Agriculture.
41 (h) The office of the State Historic Preservation Officer.
42 (2) As used in this section, “permit” has the meaning given that term in ORS 183.700.
43 (3) Not later than 120 days after the effective date of this 2026 Act, an agency shall pub-
44 lish a catalog of permits issued by the agency that are related to or have an impact on eco-
45 nomic development projects. For each permit issued by the agency that is related to or has
[3]

C-Eng. HB 4084
1 an impact on economic development projects, the catalog must include:
2 (a) A description of the permit.
3 (b) The duration of the permit.
4 (c) The statutory authority, regulatory authority or other authority for issuing the per-
5 mit.
6 (d) The method by which the agency processes incomplete applications for permits and,
7 if readily available, the annual number of incomplete applications an agency generally re-
8 ceives.
9 (e) Any statutory, regulatory or other authority governing the time within which the
10 agency must process applications for the permit.
11 (f) The application fee for the permit, the statutory, regulatory or other authority for the
12 application fee and when the amount of the application fee was last changed.
13 (g) An analysis identifying opportunities to streamline the approval process for the per-
14 mit, eliminate any unnecessary steps or barriers, reduce the incidence of incomplete appli-
15 cations and eliminate any obsolete or unnecessary approval processes.
16 (h) The approximate number of applications for the permit currently pending at the
17 agency and a statement of whether a backlog exists.
18 (4) Not later than 120 days after the effective date of this 2026 Act, an agency shall report
19 to the Governor on:
20 (a) Permitting programs in the agency that are not meeting reasonable processing
21 timelines.
22 (b) Opportunities to streamline and improve permit processing and meet reasonable
23 processing timelines.
24 (c) Suggestions obtained from consultation with permit applicants on permit processing.
25 (d) Opportunities to provide fee relief for delayed permit processing.
26 SECTION 6. Section 5 of this 2026 Act is repealed on January 2, 2027.
