27 (a) Identify issues with the potential to affect compliance with relevant exemption requirements,
28 including but not limited to enterprise zone boundary amendments;
29 (b) Arrange for methods and procedures to establish and verify compliance with applicable re-
30 quirements; and
31 (c) Identify the person who is obligated to notify the county assessor if requirements are not
32 satisfied.
33 (5) Upon completion of the preauthorization conference required under subsection (4) of this
34 section, the sponsor shall prepare a written summary of the conference, attach the summary to the
35 application and forward the application to the county assessor for review.
36 (6) Following the preauthorization conference under subsection (4) of this section, the sponsor
37 and the county assessor shall authorize the business firm by approving the application, if the spon-
38 sor and county assessor determine that:
39 (a) The current or proposed operations of the business firm in the enterprise zone result in the
40 firm being eligible under ORS 285C.135; and
41 (b) The firm has made the commitments and provided the other information required under
42 subsection (2) of this section.
43 (7) If the business firm seeking authorization is an eligible business firm described in ORS
44 285C.135 [(5)(b)] (4)(b), the sponsor must, as a condition of approving the application, make a formal
45 finding that the business firm is an eligible business firm under ORS 285C.135 and that the size of
[10]

C-Eng. HB 4084
1 the proposed investment, the employment at the facility of the firm or the nature of the activities
2 to be undertaken by the firm within the enterprise zone will significantly enhance the local econ-
3 omy, promote the purposes for which the zone was created and increase employment within the
4 zone.
5 (8) The approval of both the sponsor and the county assessor under this section shall be prima
6 facie evidence that the qualified property of the business firm will receive the property tax ex-
7 emption under ORS 285C.175. In approving the application, the sponsor and county assessor shall
8 provide proof of approval as directed by the Oregon Business Development Department.
9 (9) If the sponsor or county assessor fails or refuses to authorize the business firm, the business
10 firm may appeal to the Oregon Tax Court under ORS 305.404 to 305.560. The business firm shall
11 provide copies of the firm’s appeal to the sponsor, county assessor, the Department of Revenue and
12 the Oregon Business Development Department.
13 (10) Authorization under this section does not ensure that property constructed, added, modified
14 or installed by the authorized business firm will receive property tax exemption under ORS 285C.175.
15 The sponsor and the county assessor are not liable in any way if the Department of Revenue or the
16 county assessor later determines that an authorized business firm does not satisfy the requirements
17 for an exemption on qualified property.
18 (11) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, if an eligible business firm has begun or
19 completed the construction, addition, modification or installation of property that meets the quali-
20 fications of ORS 285C.180, and the property has not yet been subject to property tax after having
21 been placed in service, then, for purposes of ORS 285C.050 to 285C.250, the firm shall be authorized
22 under this section if the firm files an application that is allowed under subsection (12) of this section
23 and is otherwise authorized under this section.
24 (12) Late submission of an application under this section is allowed if:
25 (a) A rule permits late submissions of applications under this section; or
26 (b) The Department of Revenue waives filing deadline requirements under this section. The de-
27 partment shall issue a letter to the eligible business firm and zone sponsor setting forth the waiver
28 under this paragraph.
29 SECTION 11a. Section 11b of this 2026 Act is added to and made a part of ORS 285C.050
30 to 285C.250.
31 SECTION 11b. Notwithstanding any other provision of law, an eligible business firm may
32 not be authorized under ORS 285C.140 with respect to property consisting of a data center
33 project before the date that is 90 days following the date on which the 2027 regular session
34 of the Legislative Assembly adjourns sine die.
35 SECTION 11c. Section 11b of this 2026 Act is repealed on January 2, 2029.
36 SECTION 12. ORS 285C.180 is amended to read:
37 285C.180. (1) The following types of property are qualified for exemption under ORS 285C.175:
38 (a) A newly constructed building or structure.
39 (b) A new addition to or modification of an existing building or structure.
40 (c) Any real property machinery or equipment or personal property, whether new, used or re-
41 conditioned, that is installed on property that is owned or leased by an authorized business firm,
42 and:
43 (A) Newly purchased or leased by the firm, unless the property is described in ORS 285C.175
44 (4)(a); or
45 (B) Newly transferred into the enterprise zone from outside the county within which the site
[11]

C-Eng. HB 4084
1 of the firm is located and installed.
2 (2) Property described in subsection (1) of this section is qualified under this section only if:
3 (a) The property meets or exceeds the minimum cost requirements established under ORS
4 285C.185;
5 (b) The property satisfies applicable usage, lease or location requirements established under
6 ORS 285C.185;
7 (c) The property was constructed, added, modified or installed to further the production of in-
8 come;
9 (d) The property is owned or leased by an authorized business firm;
10 (e) The location of the property corresponds to the location as set forth in the application for
11 authorization of the business firm and consists of a single site or multiple sites adjacent to or having
12 comparable proximity to each other, within the boundaries of the enterprise zone;
13 (f) The property is the same general type of property as described in the application for au-
14 thorization; and
15 (g) In the case of an eligible business firm described in ORS 285C.135 [(5)(b)] (4)(b), the actual
16 investment at the facility of the firm is consistent with the description set forth in the application
17 for authorization.
18 (3) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, the following property is not qualified for ex-
19 emption under ORS 285C.175:
20 (a) Land.
21 (b) Property that was not in use or occupancy for more than a 180-day period that ends during
22 the preceding assessment year.
23 (c) On-site developments that, consistent with ORS 307.010, are assessed as land.
24 (d) Noninventory supplies, including but not limited to lubricants.
25 (e) Any operator-driven item of machinery or equipment or any vehicle, if the item or vehicle
26 moves by internal motorized power. An item or vehicle described in this paragraph includes but is
27 not limited to an item or vehicle that moves within an enclosed space.
28 (f) Any device or rolling stock that is pulled, pushed or carried by a vehicle that is suitable as
29 a mode of transportation beyond the enterprise zone boundary.
30 (4) Subsection (3)(b) of this section does not apply to the first assessment year for which the
31 property is exempt under ORS 285C.175.
32 (5) For purposes of this section and ORS 285C.175, property includes any portion or incremental
33 unit of property that is newly constructed or installed, or that is a new addition to or modification
34 of an existing building or structure.
35 SECTION 13. ORS 285C.155 is amended to read:
36 285C.155. For purposes of ORS 285C.200 [(2)] (3):
37 (1) The sponsor of an enterprise zone, at the time authorization is sought by a business firm
38 under ORS 285C.140, shall establish a minimum number of employees the firm must maintain in the
39 enterprise zone throughout the exemption period.
40 (2) The sponsor, at the time authorization is sought by a business firm under ORS 285C.140, may
41 establish other reasonable conditions with which the firm must comply in order for qualified prop-
42 erty of the firm to be exempt under ORS 285C.175.
43 (3) Employment requirements and other conditions established by the sponsor under this section
44 shall be set forth in a resolution adopted by the governing body of the sponsor at the time the
45 sponsor approves the application of the business firm for authorization under ORS 285C.140.
[12]

C-Eng. HB 4084
1 (4) A resolution adopted pursuant to this section may be modified at the request of the business
2 firm at any time prior to the start of the first tax year for which an exemption under ORS 285C.175
3 is claimed.
4 SECTION 14. ORS 285C.205 is amended to read:
5 285C.205. The requirements of ORS 285C.200 [(2)(b)(B)] (3)(b)(B) are met if the qualified business
6 firm does all of the following:
7 (1) The firm demonstrates at least a 10 percent increase in productivity no later than 18 months
8 following January 1 of the first assessment year for which an exemption under ORS 285C.175 is
9 claimed. Unless further specified by the sponsor of the enterprise zone through the resolution
10 adopted under ORS 285C.155:
11 (a) The increase must be in business operations of the firm that are using qualified property
12 receiving the exemption;
13 (b) Productivity is measured by dividing physical units or quantity of output by the number of
14 labor hours engaged in the operations that produced the physical units or quantity of output; and
15 (c) The base level of productivity shall be established over a minimum 12-month period preceding
16 the date on which the qualified property is placed in service.
17 (2) The firm maintains or exceeds the 10 percent increase in productivity under subsection (1)
18 of this section as an annual average rate for each subsequent assessment year during the remainder
19 of the exemption period.
20 (3) On or before April 1 of each of the first three assessment years for which an exemption is
21 claimed, the firm deposits into an account established by the sponsor an amount equal to 25 percent
22 of the estimated tax savings arising from the exemption for that year. The sponsor may adopt addi-
23 tional specifications or requirements applicable to this subsection in the resolution the sponsor
24 adopts under ORS 285C.155. Consistent with this subsection and any additional specifications or
25 requirements adopted by the sponsor:
26 (a) For up to 30 months following the relevant April 1 date for which a deposit is made, the firm
27 may draw from the account amounts equal to any expense incurred for training or retraining em-
28 ployees to promote or facilitate productivity increases under this section, except that the total
29 amount withdrawn from the account for that deposit may not exceed $3,500 per trained employee;
30 (b) Any amount attributable to the deposit that remains in the account after the 30-month period
31 in which firm withdrawals may be made under paragraph (a) of this subsection shall be transferred
32 to a special fund for use by local publicly funded job training providers; and
33 (c) No more than 18 months after the deposit, the estimated tax savings on which the deposit
34 was based shall be reconciled with the actual tax savings arising from the exemption. The recon-
35 ciliation shall be accomplished by the firm immediately making a further deposit into the account
36 to cover any shortfall or by being reimbursed from the account for any surplus. A deposit or re-
37 imbursement made pursuant to this paragraph does not affect withdrawals or transfers that occur
38 as a result of paragraph (a) or (b) of this subsection.
39 SECTION 15. ORS 285C.210 is amended to read:
40 285C.210. (1) For purposes of ORS 285C.175, 285C.200 and 285C.240, except as provided in sub-
41 section (3) of this section, operations of a business firm within the enterprise zone are substantially
42 curtailed when:
43 (a) Pursuant to the initial claim of exemption and satisfaction of ORS 285C.200 (1)(c), the number
44 of employees of the firm:
45 (A) Is reduced by more than 85 percent from the highest number of employees of the firm; or
[13]

C-Eng. HB 4084
1 (B) Has been reduced by more than 50 percent from the highest number of employees of the firm
2 over two consecutive annual filing periods under ORS 285C.220 (1); or
3 (b) The annual average number of employees of the firm during the first assessment year for
4 which the exemption under ORS 285C.175 is granted, or any subsequently allowed year of exemption,
5 is reduced below the greater of:
6 (A) The annual average number of employees of the firm, averaged over the 12 months preceding
7 the date of the application for authorization, plus one employee; or
8 (B) 110 percent of the annual average number of employees of the firm, averaged over the 12
9 months preceding the date of the application for authorization.
10 (2) For the purposes of this section:
11 (a) Except as provided in paragraph (c)(A) of this subsection, the number of employees of the
12 firm is the employment of the firm, as defined in ORS 285C.200 [(7)(b)] (8)(b), on the earlier of the
13 date a claim for exemption is filed under ORS 285C.220 or April 1 of the year in which the ex-
14 emption is initially claimed under ORS 285C.175 and following each assessment year of the ex-
15 emption, including after the last such assessment year.
16 (b) Except as provided in paragraph (c)(B) of this subsection, the annual average number of
17 employees of the firm is the number of employees of the firm averaged over the course of each as-
18 sessment year in which an exemption under ORS 285C.175 is allowed, using employment figures for
19 no fewer than four equivalent periods during the year.
20 (c) For the first assessment year for which an authorized business firm that qualifies under ORS
21 285C.200 [(5)] (6) claims an exemption under ORS 285C.175, substantial curtailment under subsection
22 (1)(a)(A) or (b) of this section shall be determined by:
23 (A) Combining the number of employees of the firm and the number of employees at any appli-
24 cable site of the firm outside the enterprise zone; and
25 (B) Combining the annual average number of employees of the firm with the annual average
26 number of employees at any applicable site of the firm outside the enterprise zone.
27 (3) Operations of a business firm are not substantially curtailed under this section during a pe-
28 riod of suspension as otherwise provided in ORS 285C.203.
29 SECTION 16. If Senate Bill 1507 becomes law, section 12, chapter , Oregon Laws 2026
30 (Enrolled Senate Bill 1507), is amended to read:
31 Sec. 12. [(1) A credit against taxes that are otherwise due under ORS chapter 316 or, if the tax-
32 payer is a corporation, under ORS chapter 317 or 318 is allowed to a taxpayer for each new job in
33 Oregon created by the taxpayer during the tax year.]
34 (1) As used in this section:
35 (a)(A) “Advanced manufacturing” means activities that:
36 (i) Depend on the use and coordination of information, automation, computation, soft-
37 ware, industrial sensors and networking;
38 (ii) Make use of newly developed materials and processes enabled by the physical and bi-
39 ological sciences, including but not limited to nanotechnology, chemistry and biology;
40 (iii) Involve both new ways to manufacture existing products and the manufacture of new
41 products emerging from new advanced technologies; or
42 (iv) As applied to biotechnology and life sciences activities, are related research, devel-
43 opment, scale-up and enabling technology activities integral to the production of biological,
44 medical or biobased products.
45 (B) “Advanced manufacturing” does not include activities that are primarily:
[14]

C-Eng. HB 4084
1 (i) Routine assembly, packaging, labeling, sorting, warehousing, storage or distribution;
2 (ii) Basic fabrication, machining or processing that does not incorporate advanced tech-
3 nologies or materially transform products or production processes;
4 (iii) Maintenance, repair or refurbishment of machinery, equipment or products; or
5 (iv) Administrative, clerical, sales, marketing or other nonproduction activities.
6 (b) “Clean technology” means the manufacture or provision of, or research or develop-
7 ment supporting the manufacture or provision of, products or services that enable energy
8 to be produced from renewable sources, that reduce negative environmental impacts or that
9 reduce energy consumption.
10 (c) “High technology” means software, information technology and semiconductor or re-
11 lated device manufacturing.
12 (d) “Qualified industry” means businesses that operate in any of the following sectors:
13 (A) Advanced manufacturing;
14 (B) Bioscience and biotechnology;
15 (C) Clean technology;
16 (D) Food and beverage processing;
17 (E) Forestry and wood products;
18 (F) High technology; or
19 (G) Outdoor gear and apparel.
20 (2) A credit against taxes that are otherwise due under ORS chapter 316 or, if the tax-
21 payer is a corporation, under ORS chapter 317 or 318 is allowed to a taxpayer that is engaged
22 in a qualified industry as a primary business, for each new job in Oregon created by the
23 taxpayer during the tax year in a qualified industry.
24 [(2)(a)] (3)(a) The credit allowed under this section shall be in the amount of $1,000 for each net
25 new job created by a taxpayer in the tax year, but a taxpayer may not be certified for and may not
26 receive a credit for more than 10 new jobs created per tax year.
27 (b) In order to be considered in the determination under this section of the eligibility and al-
28 lowable credit amount for any taxpayer, an employment position must have compensation that is
29 equal to or greater than 150 percent of the applicable minimum wage determined under ORS 653.025.
30 (c) The number of net new jobs created by the taxpayer in a tax year shall be determined by
31 comparing the average annual covered employment of the taxpayer for the 12 months ending on
32 June 30 of the calendar year in which the taxpayer’s tax year began and for which the credit is
33 sought, with the 12 months ending on June 30 of the immediately preceding calendar year.
34 [(3) Prior to claiming the credit allowed under this section, a taxpayer seeking to claim the credit
35 is required to receive written certification of eligibility from the Oregon Business Development De-
36 partment. In order to receive certification, a taxpayer must attest that the taxpayer has created new jobs
37 sufficient to be eligible for the amount of credit sought, has met the wage requirements of subsection
38 (2)(b) of this section and is otherwise in compliance with this section. The certification shall indicate
39 the amount of the credit to which the taxpayer is entitled for the tax year.]
40 (4) Prior to claiming the credit allowed under this section, a taxpayer seeking to claim
41 the credit is required to receive written certification of eligibility from the Oregon Business
42 Development Department. In order to receive certification, a taxpayer must attest that the
43 taxpayer:
44 (a) Is engaged as the taxpayer’s primary business in a qualified industry;
45 (b) Has created new jobs sufficient to be eligible for the amount of credit sought; and
[15]

C-Eng. HB 4084
1 (c) Has met the wage requirements of subsection (3)(b) of this section and is otherwise
2 in compliance with this section.
3 (5) The certification shall indicate the amount of the credit to which the taxpayer is en-
4 titled for the tax year.
5 [(4)] (6) The credit allowed under this section may not exceed the tax liability of the taxpayer
6 for the tax year.
7 [(5)] (7) Any tax credit otherwise allowable under this section that is not used by the taxpayer
8 in a particular tax year may be carried forward and offset against the taxpayer’s tax liability for
9 the next succeeding tax year. Any credit remaining unused in the next succeeding tax year may be
10 carried forward and used in the second succeeding tax year, and likewise any credit not used in that
11 second succeeding tax year may be carried forward and used in the third succeeding tax year but
12 may not be carried forward for any other succeeding tax year.
13 [(6)] (8) The Oregon Business Development Department shall provide information to the De-
14 partment of Revenue about all taxpayers that are eligible for a tax credit under this section, if re-
15 quired by ORS 315.058.
16 [(7)] (9) Information received by the Oregon Business Development Department pursuant to this
17 section may be used only for the purpose of certification and administration of the credit. The
18 Oregon Business Development Department may disclose this information to entities other than the
19 Department of Revenue only if the information is sufficiently aggregated or anonymized to protect
20 the identity and confidential information of taxpayers.
21 [(8)] (10) The Director of the Oregon Business Development Department may order the suspen-
22 sion or revocation of a certification issued under this section, as provided in ORS 315.061.
23 [(9) The Oregon Business Development Department shall by rule establish:]
24 [(a) The form and content of and deadlines for applications for the credit allowed under this sec-
25 tion.]
26 [(b) Methodology for determining net new jobs created, as provided in subsection (2) of this section,
27 in the instance of a merger, conversion, reorganization, consolidation or acquisition affecting a tax-
28 payer.]
29 (11) The Oregon Business Development Department shall by rule:
30 (a) Establish the form and content of and deadlines for applications for the credit allowed
31 under this section.
32 (b) Establish methodology for determining net new jobs created, as provided in subsection
33 (3) of this section, in the instance of a merger, conversion, reorganization, consolidation or
34 acquisition affecting a taxpayer.
35 (c) Further define the term “qualified industry” for purposes of this section.
36 SECTION 17. This 2026 Act takes effect on the 91st day after the date on which the 2026
37 regular session of the Eighty-third Legislative Assembly adjourns sine die.
